TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Equilibrium Conflict Model of Land Tenure in Hunter‐Gatherer Societies
AU  - Baker, Matthew J.
Y1  - 2003/02/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/344800
DO  - 10.1086/344800
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 124
EP  - 173
VL  - 111
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - I apply features of the economics of conflict and spatial competition in developing a model of the emergence of land ownership in hunter?gatherer societies. Tenure regimes are the result of interactions between those seeking to defend claims to land and those seeking to infringe on those claims. The model highlights the dependence of land ownership on ecological parameters, such as resource density and predictability, and allows for situational ownership, in which the nature of ownership changes as realized ecological conditions change. The paper concludes with a comparative assessment of tenure across a representative sample of hunter?gatherer peoples.
AB  - I apply features of the economics of conflict and spatial competition in developing a model of the emergence of land ownership in hunter?gatherer societies. Tenure regimes are the result of interactions between those seeking to defend claims to land and those seeking to infringe on those claims. The model highlights the dependence of land ownership on ecological parameters, such as resource density and predictability, and allows for situational ownership, in which the nature of ownership changes as realized ecological conditions change. The paper concludes with a comparative assessment of tenure across a representative sample of hunter?gatherer peoples.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/344800
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/344800
Y2  - 2024/03/19
